# Pin the build target to Next.js's documented modern default
# (https://nextjs.org/docs/architecture/supported-browsers). This is a
# REGRESSION-GUARD + SELF-DOC, not a bundle-size win:
#
#   * Next/SWC already defaults to exactly these targets, so this file does
#     not change the build output by a single byte. Its job is to stop a
#     future dependency or edit from silently *loosening* the target — a
#     looser target would make SWC transpile our first-party code and inject
#     extra core-js polyfills.
#
#   * It does NOT remove the "legacy JavaScript" PageSpeed flag. That ~112 KB
#     chunk is Next's own framework polyfill (next/dist/build/polyfills/
#     polyfill-nomodule.js, core-js v3.38.1). It is emitted as
#     `<script ... noModule>`, so every ES-module-capable browser
#     (Chrome 111+/Safari 16.4+ — essentially all real traffic) skips
#     downloading it. It is framework-level and unconditional: tightening
#     this target does not strip it (and an ultra-modern target instead
#     breaks `next/font/local`). Removing it would require patching Next.

